Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.160 --> 00:00:03.760
Prof: So time to start.
 

00:00:03.760 --> 00:00:07.280
So let me begin by reviewing a
little bit of the dynamic

00:00:07.280 --> 00:00:10.672
hedging which I could have
described a little bit more

00:00:10.672 --> 00:00:12.080
clearly last time.
 

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:17.151
It's a very important idea and
I made a little bit of a mess of

00:00:17.151 --> 00:00:17.560
it.
 

00:00:17.560 --> 00:00:19.555
I didn't make that big a mess
of it, but a little bit of a

00:00:19.555 --> 00:00:20.010
mess of it.
 

00:00:20.010 --> 00:00:24.301
So let's be a little bit
careful now about who knows what

00:00:24.301 --> 00:00:26.140
and what you're doing.
 

00:00:26.140 --> 00:00:30.765
So we said imagine somebody who
knows that the probability the

00:00:30.765 --> 00:00:35.240
Yankees are going to win the
World Series is 60 percent,

00:00:35.240 --> 00:00:39.600
and therefore each game of the
World Series is 60 percent,

00:00:39.600 --> 00:00:44.024
and knows that the probability
the Phillies win the game is 40

00:00:44.024 --> 00:00:44.750
percent.
 

00:00:44.750 --> 00:00:49.403
So suppose that he finds
somebody who is willing to bet

00:00:49.403 --> 00:00:51.730
with him on the Phillies.
 

00:00:51.730 --> 00:00:54.210
So he can win 100 dollars if
the Yankees win.

00:00:54.210 --> 00:00:57.410
He has to pay 100 dollars if
the Yankees lose.

00:00:57.410 --> 00:01:00.368
Now, his expected payoff is 20.
 

00:01:00.368 --> 00:01:04.183
He should take the bet because
if the person's willing to bet

00:01:04.183 --> 00:01:06.620
at even odds,
the Phillies fan's willing to

00:01:06.620 --> 00:01:09.120
bet at even odds and he knows
the odds are 60/40,

00:01:09.120 --> 00:01:11.519
on expectation he's going to
make 20.

00:01:11.519 --> 00:01:14.578
So it's clear what he should
do, but the problem is he's

00:01:14.578 --> 00:01:15.578
subject to risk.
 

00:01:15.578 --> 00:01:19.849
Although he's right about the
odds he could still,

00:01:19.849 --> 00:01:22.129
even though he's done the smart
thing,

00:01:22.129 --> 00:01:25.563
he could still end up losing
100 dollars which could be a

00:01:25.563 --> 00:01:26.730
disaster for him.
 

00:01:26.730 --> 00:01:30.629
So what he would like to do is
to hedge his bets.

00:01:30.629 --> 00:01:32.470
Now, what does it mean hedge
his bet?

00:01:32.470 --> 00:01:36.900
Well, suppose there was another
bookie who was willing to bet at

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:40.840
60/40 odds in either direction
then what should he do?

00:01:40.840 --> 00:01:46.144
Well, if he can find another
bookie who was willing to bet at

00:01:46.144 --> 00:01:51.093
60/40 odds he should try and
lock in 20 dollars no matter

00:01:51.093 --> 00:01:51.890
what.
 

00:01:51.890 --> 00:01:59.500
So he should do this bet.
 

00:01:59.500 --> 00:02:02.858
He should bet with the other
bookie 80 dollars.

00:02:02.858 --> 00:02:06.700
He'd be willing to give up 80
dollars if the Yankees won in

00:02:06.700 --> 00:02:09.878
order to win 120 dollars if the
Phillies win,

00:02:09.878 --> 00:02:13.397
and that's a fair bet according
to the other bookie because it's

00:02:13.397 --> 00:02:15.492
60/40 odds,
60 percent of this and 40

00:02:15.492 --> 00:02:18.990
percent of that,
this is 3 to 2 odds so it's a

00:02:18.990 --> 00:02:19.870
fair bet.
 

00:02:19.870 --> 00:02:22.752
So in other words,
he makes money by taking

00:02:22.752 --> 00:02:26.116
advantage of the Philly fan to
bet on the Yankees,

00:02:26.116 --> 00:02:28.449
but that subjects him to risk.
 

00:02:28.449 --> 00:02:32.150
So in order to minimize the
risk he hedges his bet.

00:02:32.150 --> 00:02:33.830
That's where the expression
came from.

00:02:33.830 --> 00:02:37.628
He hedges that bet by betting
in the opposite direction,

00:02:37.628 --> 00:02:40.550
on--betting on the Phillies
with his bookie,

00:02:40.550 --> 00:02:45.454
in the opposite direction,
but standing to lose less than

00:02:45.454 --> 00:02:48.024
he,
you know, he's betting in this

00:02:48.024 --> 00:02:50.520
proportion,
in this amount so that he gets

00:02:50.520 --> 00:02:51.538
20 no matter what.
 

00:02:51.538 --> 00:02:53.990
So he's locked in his 20-dollar
profit.

00:02:53.990 --> 00:02:55.949
So that was where we began.
 

00:02:55.949 --> 00:02:58.187
Now, let's just think about it
a little bit more carefully than

00:02:58.187 --> 00:02:58.729
I did before.
 

00:02:58.729 --> 00:03:02.068
Somebody, in fact,
basically asked this question.

00:03:02.068 --> 00:03:05.492
Is he really making money
because he understands better

00:03:05.492 --> 00:03:08.218
the odds of the Yankees winning
the game?

00:03:08.218 --> 00:03:11.800
Is he making money because he
knows the odds are 60/40 and the

00:03:11.800 --> 00:03:14.090
poor Philly fan thinks they're
50/50?

00:03:14.090 --> 00:03:15.370
The answer is no.
 

00:03:15.370 --> 00:03:16.750
That's not why he's making
money.

00:03:16.750 --> 00:03:20.169
It doesn't matter what the odds
are of the Yankees winning.

00:03:20.169 --> 00:03:23.955
He's winning because he's
managed to arbitrage two

00:03:23.955 --> 00:03:27.247
different betters,
namely the Philly fan and the

00:03:27.247 --> 00:03:29.566
other bookie,
and the fact that they differ

00:03:29.566 --> 00:03:32.532
in their beliefs,
the fact that he can trade with

00:03:32.532 --> 00:03:35.780
the bookie at 3 to 2 odds
whatever bet he wants,

00:03:35.780 --> 00:03:40.030
and the Philly fan is trading
at different odds with him.

00:03:40.030 --> 00:03:42.440
That's what enables him to make
his profit.

00:03:42.440 --> 00:03:46.301
So how did he make the
arbitrage--so what is an

00:03:46.301 --> 00:03:47.310
arbitrage?
 

00:03:47.310 --> 00:03:50.466
An arbitrage is,
you find two bets which are

00:03:50.466 --> 00:03:54.650
more or less the same thing,
which in fact are exactly the

00:03:54.650 --> 00:03:58.099
same thing, but trade at a
different price.

00:03:58.099 --> 00:04:03.080
So what are the two bets?
 

00:04:03.080 --> 00:04:12.693
Well, there's the Philly bet,
the Philly fan bet,

00:04:12.693 --> 00:04:24.709
and then there's the bookie bet
plus borrowing 20 dollars.

00:04:24.709 --> 00:04:27.540
So he's going to make 20 for
sure.

00:04:27.540 --> 00:04:30.732
So he could make the 20 at the
beginning just by borrowing

00:04:30.732 --> 00:04:32.019
against his winnings.
 

00:04:32.019 --> 00:04:37.829
Then he'd have 20 at the very
beginning and his payoffs from

00:04:37.829 --> 00:04:43.639
the Philly fan bet would be
exactly--he'd owe the 20 so he'd

00:04:43.639 --> 00:04:45.509
have minus 100.
 

00:04:45.509 --> 00:04:52.091
So this bet is he'd be able to
get 20 at the beginning,

00:04:52.091 --> 00:04:57.089
but he'd have to pay minus 100
and 100.

00:04:57.089 --> 00:05:05.947
He'd pay 100 dollars if the
Yankees won, and get 100 dollars

00:05:05.947 --> 00:05:09.250
if the Phillies won.
 

00:05:09.250 --> 00:05:14.144
And so that way he'd cancel his
bet at the end and end up with

00:05:14.144 --> 00:05:15.910
20 dollars for sure.
 

00:05:15.910 --> 00:05:18.608
So just to say it again,
he's made money apparently

00:05:18.608 --> 00:05:21.360
because he knows more than the
Philly fan knows,

00:05:21.360 --> 00:05:24.949
but actually in order to
guarantee that he doesn't run a

00:05:24.949 --> 00:05:27.430
risk he has to find another
trader,

00:05:27.430 --> 00:05:30.990
and it's the presence of the
other trader who's really giving

00:05:30.990 --> 00:05:34.629
him his profit opportunity,
not his superior knowledge.

00:05:34.629 --> 00:05:37.093
And the fact that he has two
different traders--and so why

00:05:37.093 --> 00:05:38.649
does that give him an
opportunity?

00:05:38.649 --> 00:05:43.418
Because he can arrange a bet
with the Philly fan and a bet

00:05:43.418 --> 00:05:48.591
with the other bookie,
but combined with borrowing the

00:05:48.591 --> 00:05:54.459
money so that in the end he's
going to just get 0 payoffs.

00:05:54.459 --> 00:05:56.790
Putting together the Philly fan
bet,

00:05:56.790 --> 00:05:59.564
and the bookie fan bet,
and borrowing 20 dollars he

00:05:59.564 --> 00:06:01.838
gets 20 dollars at the very
beginning,

00:06:01.838 --> 00:06:05.100
and on net he has nothing at
the end,

00:06:05.100 --> 00:06:08.430
so whatever losses he got from
the Phillies he made up from the

00:06:08.430 --> 00:06:09.129
bookie bet.
 

00:06:09.129 --> 00:06:12.100
Whatever losses he had from the
bookie bet he made up for it

00:06:12.100 --> 00:06:13.410
with the Philly fan bet.
 

00:06:13.410 --> 00:06:17.569
So arbitrage relies on
replication.

00:06:17.569 --> 00:06:24.439
Somehow through some other
bet--he was able to hedge his

00:06:24.439 --> 00:06:25.939
other bet.
 

00:06:25.939 --> 00:06:29.843
He was able to hedge his
Phillies bet by replicating the

00:06:29.843 --> 00:06:33.819
bet with somebody else combined
with borrowing to produce

00:06:33.819 --> 00:06:36.730
exactly the same payoffs in the
end,

00:06:36.730 --> 00:06:39.079
or the negative of the payoffs
in the end,

00:06:39.079 --> 00:06:41.860
and yet for a different price
at the beginning.

00:06:41.860 --> 00:06:44.934
The Philly fan didn't demand
any money upfront to make this

00:06:44.934 --> 00:06:46.629
(100, minus 100) bet with him.
 

00:06:46.629 --> 00:06:51.584
And with the bookie he's able
to get 20 dollars upfront and

00:06:51.584 --> 00:06:56.199
make this the opposite bet,
the (minus 100,100) bet.

00:06:56.199 --> 00:06:59.711
So by getting more money
upfront and doing the opposite

00:06:59.711 --> 00:07:03.418
bet with the bookie he can end
up completely canceling the

00:07:03.418 --> 00:07:05.274
Philly bet,
Philly fan bet,

00:07:05.274 --> 00:07:07.230
and that's how he makes his
profit.

00:07:07.230 --> 00:07:10.069
So that was the first idea.
 

00:07:10.069 --> 00:07:11.439
So what have I clarified?
 

00:07:11.439 --> 00:07:14.410
What I've clarified is that it
wasn't his superior knowledge,

00:07:14.410 --> 00:07:17.113
it was the presence of two
different traders that enabled

00:07:17.113 --> 00:07:20.115
him to make his profit,
and I've clarified the method

00:07:20.115 --> 00:07:21.620
that he made the profit.
 

00:07:21.620 --> 00:07:25.488
The profit wasn't just kind of
mixing in another bet,

00:07:25.488 --> 00:07:29.283
it was really cleverly
arranging to undo totally the

00:07:29.283 --> 00:07:30.550
original bet.
 

00:07:30.550 --> 00:07:34.627
So he got actually 0 in the end
and ended up with 20 dollars at

00:07:34.627 --> 00:07:35.680
the beginning.
 

00:07:35.680 --> 00:07:41.290
So let's just see now what you
would do in a dynamic situation.

00:07:41.290 --> 00:07:41.990
Yes?
 

00:07:41.990 --> 00:07:42.600
Student: I apologize.
 

00:07:42.600 --> 00:07:45.410
I understand how this locks him
into that $20 dollars,

00:07:45.410 --> 00:07:47.245
and how it makes sure he
doesn't incur the losses that he

00:07:47.245 --> 00:07:49.180
might have occurred,
but why would he do this if he

00:07:49.180 --> 00:07:51.579
has 20 dollars at the beginning
and all this does is make sure

00:07:51.579 --> 00:07:53.940
no matter what he ends up with
the 20 dollars at the end?

00:07:53.940 --> 00:07:55.319
Prof: Why would he do
what at all?

00:07:55.319 --> 00:07:56.920
Student: This arbitrage
at all, any of the bets.

00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:59.322
It seems like no matter what
whether the Yankees or lose he

00:07:59.322 --> 00:08:00.399
ends up with 20 dollars.
 

00:08:00.399 --> 00:08:02.550
Why didn't he just keep his 20
dollars and not bet?

00:08:02.550 --> 00:08:04.230
Prof: He didn't have 20
dollars to begin with.

00:08:04.230 --> 00:08:05.560
He had no dollars.
 

00:08:05.560 --> 00:08:08.915
So he went and found the Philly
fan and he made a bet against

00:08:08.915 --> 00:08:10.649
the Philly fan with no money.
 

00:08:10.649 --> 00:08:14.524
The Philly fan was willing to
bet him 100 dollars on the

00:08:14.524 --> 00:08:15.300
Phillies.
 

00:08:15.300 --> 00:08:16.740
So he gets 100 if the Yankees
win.

00:08:16.740 --> 00:08:19.040
He pays the fan 100 if the
Phillies win.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:20.740
It didn't cost any money to do
that.

00:08:20.740 --> 00:08:24.120
Then he goes out and makes
another bet with the bookie.

00:08:24.120 --> 00:08:25.680
Again, it doesn't cost him any
money.

00:08:25.680 --> 00:08:29.110
He gives up 80 dollars if the
Yankees win, but he gets $120 if

00:08:29.110 --> 00:08:30.180
the Phillies win.
 

00:08:30.180 --> 00:08:33.398
So he's spent no money at all
and his total profit is 20

00:08:33.398 --> 00:08:34.509
dollars for sure.
 

00:08:34.509 --> 00:08:36.816
So what could he do since he
knows he's going to make 20

00:08:36.816 --> 00:08:38.200
dollars for sure in the future?
 

00:08:38.200 --> 00:08:40.596
He could just borrow it at the
beginning if the interest rate's

00:08:40.596 --> 00:08:42.215
0,
have 20 dollars at the

00:08:42.215 --> 00:08:45.908
beginning, end up with 0 no
matter what the uncertainty is

00:08:45.908 --> 00:08:48.500
and put the 20 dollars in his
pocket.

00:08:48.500 --> 00:08:52.979
So that's another way of saying
the same thing which is that he

00:08:52.979 --> 00:08:54.721
could,
by combining the bets,

00:08:54.721 --> 00:08:57.746
put money in his pocket in at
the beginning and no matter what

00:08:57.746 --> 00:09:00.774
happens in the future he doesn't
have to give anybody any more

00:09:00.774 --> 00:09:01.320
money.
 

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:02.090
So that's what he's done.
 

00:09:02.090 --> 00:09:03.230
That's what an arbitrage is.
 

00:09:03.230 --> 00:09:06.961
You put money in your pocket in
the present and in the future

00:09:06.961 --> 00:09:09.139
you never have to face a
problem.

00:09:09.139 --> 00:09:13.681
You've always got money that's
going out in one hand you're

00:09:13.681 --> 00:09:16.028
getting from the other hand.
 

00:09:16.028 --> 00:09:19.840
Now, in a dynamic situation you
can do the same thing.

00:09:19.840 --> 00:09:22.259
So I'm just reinterpreting what
we did before a little bit.

00:09:22.259 --> 00:09:25.019
So in the dynamic situation
what are you doing?

00:09:25.019 --> 00:09:29.586
The Philly fan now is betting
on the whole World Series even

00:09:29.586 --> 00:09:32.450
though you know the odds are
60/40.

00:09:32.450 --> 00:09:35.046
So now that's an even worse bet
by the Philly fan if you're

00:09:35.046 --> 00:09:37.912
right about the odds because the
chances are even higher that the

00:09:37.912 --> 00:09:40.330
Yankees are going to win the
series than one game.

00:09:40.330 --> 00:09:42.830
The odds, we know,
are 71 percent.

00:09:42.830 --> 00:09:46.803
So by backward induction we did
this calculation to say your

00:09:46.803 --> 00:09:48.960
expected payoff is 42 dollars.
 

00:09:48.960 --> 00:09:52.263
So let's suppose now--but now
the key is that you're making

00:09:52.263 --> 00:09:55.678
money not just because you know
better what the odds are,

00:09:55.678 --> 00:09:59.559
you're making money because
there's another bookie standing

00:09:59.559 --> 00:10:03.908
there always ready to trade with
you at 60/40 odds in any game.

00:10:03.908 --> 00:10:07.761
So the presence of the second
bookie, even if you knew

00:10:07.761 --> 00:10:11.541
nothing, would enable you to
make money in this case,

00:10:11.541 --> 00:10:14.740
lock in a profit for sure of 42
dollars.

00:10:14.740 --> 00:10:17.369
Now, how do you know that you
can lock in a profit for sure of

00:10:17.369 --> 00:10:17.928
42 dollars?
 

00:10:17.928 --> 00:10:22.450
Well, it's now done by dynamic
hedging.

00:10:22.450 --> 00:10:26.990
You have to lay off part of
your bet,

00:10:26.990 --> 00:10:29.916
a little part each day,
each game and the amount that

00:10:29.916 --> 00:10:32.730
you lay off is going to depend
on what happens,

00:10:32.730 --> 00:10:33.799
so that's why it's dynamic.
 

00:10:33.799 --> 00:10:35.558
It's a complicated calculation.
 

00:10:35.558 --> 00:10:38.679
So it seems almost hopeless to
figure out what to do.

00:10:38.679 --> 00:10:40.700
I'm betting on the whole series.
 

00:10:40.700 --> 00:10:43.178
Many different things can
happen.

00:10:43.178 --> 00:10:45.009
The Phillies could win the
first game.

00:10:45.009 --> 00:10:46.200
The Yankees could win the first
game.

00:10:46.200 --> 00:10:47.840
Lots of things could happen.
 

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:51.559
By the end I want to make sure
I've locked in my profit for

00:10:51.559 --> 00:10:52.009
sure.
 

00:10:52.009 --> 00:10:53.538
How can I do that?
 

00:10:53.538 --> 00:11:00.450
Well, the key is to think about
marking to market.

00:11:00.450 --> 00:11:04.120
Just as we said,
if you're assessing your

00:11:04.120 --> 00:11:07.686
position correctly,
even though the World Series

00:11:07.686 --> 00:11:11.101
takes 7 games,
if you were reporting to your

00:11:11.101 --> 00:11:13.129
investors,
your hedge fund,

00:11:13.129 --> 00:11:16.440
you're reporting to your
investors how you're doing,

00:11:16.440 --> 00:11:18.928
you should be telling them
after the first game,

00:11:18.928 --> 00:11:20.528
you know, at the beginning
you're telling them,

00:11:20.528 --> 00:11:22.028
"Look, I'm going to make
42 dollars.

00:11:22.028 --> 00:11:23.490
I expect to make 42
dollars."

00:11:23.490 --> 00:11:26.360
After the Yankees win the first
game it looks like you're going

00:11:26.360 --> 00:11:28.116
to make 60,
you know, now things are

00:11:28.116 --> 00:11:30.470
better, you expect to make 64
dollars on average,

00:11:30.470 --> 00:11:33.895
but if the Yankees lost the
first game you'd only expect to

00:11:33.895 --> 00:11:35.548
make 9 dollars on average.
 

00:11:35.548 --> 00:11:39.168
So after the first game you go
from thinking you're going to

00:11:39.168 --> 00:11:41.928
make 42 to being even more
optimistic now,

00:11:41.928 --> 00:11:45.808
you're going to make 64 or
you're going to make 9.

00:11:45.808 --> 00:11:51.230
So 60 percent times 64 40
percent of 9 is 42.

00:11:51.230 --> 00:11:55.155
So if you were telling your
investors properly how you stood

00:11:55.155 --> 00:11:59.081
after the very first game you
might have to tell them you've

00:11:59.081 --> 00:12:03.009
lost 33 of the 42 dollars that
you told them before you were

00:12:03.009 --> 00:12:04.340
going to make.
 

00:12:04.340 --> 00:12:07.230
So you'd already be running a
risk.

00:12:07.230 --> 00:12:11.076
You really only care,
maybe, about getting money for

00:12:11.076 --> 00:12:13.770
sure by the end,
but if you're doing proper

00:12:13.770 --> 00:12:16.878
accounting you should be worried
all the way along whether you're

00:12:16.878 --> 00:12:18.139
making or losing money.
 

00:12:18.139 --> 00:12:23.028
And that's the key to how to
have no risk by the end.

00:12:23.028 --> 00:12:25.658
You just run no risk at all the
in between stages.

00:12:25.658 --> 00:12:29.592
So all you have to do is make a
bet with the bookie who's

00:12:29.592 --> 00:12:33.666
standing by to make 33 dollars
in case the Phillies win the

00:12:33.666 --> 00:12:34.720
first game.
 

00:12:34.720 --> 00:12:38.453
You're making a one game bet in
exchange for losing 22 dollars

00:12:38.453 --> 00:12:39.740
if the Yankees win.
 

00:12:39.740 --> 00:12:42.719
This is still 3 to 2 odds,
so the bookie's willing to do

00:12:42.719 --> 00:12:42.990
it.
 

