bet.

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:12.352
So you just keep proceeding
down the tree locking in where

00:17:12.352 --> 00:17:16.130
you were before and so by
induction you've locked in 42.

00:17:16.130 --> 00:17:19.015
So that's what you're doing,
and the bet is changing every

00:17:19.015 --> 00:17:19.368
time.
 

00:17:19.368 --> 00:17:21.730
So what do you think the bet is
here, by the way?

00:17:21.730 --> 00:17:32.180
The bet here you could go from
9 to 36 or minus 32.

00:17:32.180 --> 00:17:41.720
So what should you do here?
 

00:17:41.720 --> 00:17:45.348
What should you do here?
 

00:17:45.348 --> 00:17:49.048
What's the bet that you're
going to make with the bookie

00:17:49.048 --> 00:17:51.740
after the Phillies win the first
game?

00:17:51.740 --> 00:17:57.787
So it's going to be minus 27
and plus 41, and that's 3 to 2

00:17:57.787 --> 00:18:03.522
odds with some rounding,
right, 13 and 1 half times 3 is

00:18:03.522 --> 00:18:05.400
40 and 1 half.
 

00:18:05.400 --> 00:18:10.001
So it's still fair odds,
so the bookie's willing to do

00:18:10.001 --> 00:18:10.609
that.
 

00:18:10.609 --> 00:18:11.660
You've locked in 9.
 

00:18:11.660 --> 00:18:15.096
So by induction you've always
locked in where you were before

00:18:15.096 --> 00:18:18.190
and therefore you've locked in
42 all the way along.

00:18:18.190 --> 00:18:20.440
It sounds like we're locking in
9,

00:18:20.440 --> 00:18:23.102
but we're not locking in 9
because remember the first day

00:18:23.102 --> 00:18:25.905
you won 33 dollars from the
bookie when the Phillies won the

00:18:25.905 --> 00:18:26.618
first game.
 

00:18:26.618 --> 00:18:29.455
So you've locked in the 9,
but don't forget the 33 from

00:18:29.455 --> 00:18:31.819
before, so it's really you've
locked in 42.

00:18:31.819 --> 00:18:34.119
So 42's locked in the whole way.
 

00:18:34.119 --> 00:18:36.630
So that's dynamic hedging.
 

00:18:36.630 --> 00:18:41.823
You have a complicated bet that
depends on a lot of things along

00:18:41.823 --> 00:18:45.049
the way,
but you bet each time along the

00:18:45.049 --> 00:18:46.906
way,
maybe changing your bet each

00:18:46.906 --> 00:18:49.068
time depending on what's
happened so far,

00:18:49.068 --> 00:18:52.400
and that way you can lock in
whatever profit you had.

00:18:52.400 --> 00:18:57.906
So that's the thing that sports
bookies have known for a long

00:18:57.906 --> 00:18:58.548
time.
 

00:18:58.548 --> 00:19:01.826
The expression "hedging
your bets"

00:19:01.826 --> 00:19:06.320
comes from that and so that
same logic can be applied to the

00:19:06.320 --> 00:19:07.160
market.
 

00:19:07.160 --> 00:19:10.025
But remember,
the step that I didn't

00:19:10.025 --> 00:19:14.772
emphasize very much is that
although you seem to be locking

00:19:14.772 --> 00:19:18.548
in where you were before,
there's a slightly more

00:19:18.548 --> 00:19:22.732
abstract way of saying that,
that at the end you're going to

00:19:22.732 --> 00:19:24.720
get 42 dollars for sure.
 

00:19:24.720 --> 00:19:28.144
So of course you could borrow
all the way back from the

00:19:28.144 --> 00:19:31.824
beginning and get 42 dollars
immediately and then never owe

00:19:31.824 --> 00:19:35.400
anything in the future,
because whatever bet you were

00:19:35.400 --> 00:19:38.815
winning or losing with the
Philly fan you were making up

00:19:38.815 --> 00:19:41.608
for with your myriad bets with
the bookie.

00:19:41.608 --> 00:19:45.786
So it's a replication argument
that by betting sequentially

00:19:45.786 --> 00:19:48.450
with the bookie different
amounts,

00:19:48.450 --> 00:19:55.690
you're undoing the single long
bet you had with the Philly fan.

00:19:55.690 --> 00:20:01.864
So now let's move from sports,
as we did last time,

00:20:01.864 --> 00:20:03.838
to the market.
 

00:20:03.838 --> 00:20:06.588
So here we had the prepayment
spreadsheet.

00:20:06.588 --> 00:20:12.170
And so we had,
remember, this was a bond,

00:20:12.170 --> 00:20:15.558
a mortgage, a 30-year mortgage,
8 percent mortgage,

00:20:15.558 --> 00:20:21.585
and the interest rate started
off at 6 percent and it had a 20

00:20:21.585 --> 00:20:23.660
percent volatility.
 

00:20:23.660 --> 00:20:26.039
So the interest rates could
follow this process.

00:20:26.039 --> 00:20:27.028
There you see it.
 

00:20:27.028 --> 00:20:30.061
They start at 6 percent,
but they can go up or down by

00:20:30.061 --> 00:20:32.180
20 percent, basically every
period.

00:20:32.180 --> 00:20:35.998
So you assume that everybody
knows this and knows that the

00:20:35.998 --> 00:20:37.740
probabilities are 50/50.
 

00:20:37.740 --> 00:20:41.220
That's like saying you know in
advance there's a bookie out

00:20:41.220 --> 00:20:42.819
there,
that is the market,

00:20:42.819 --> 00:20:46.089
that's willing to give you,
no matter what day it is,

00:20:46.089 --> 00:20:50.250
50/50 odds of the interest rate
going up or down from then on.

00:20:50.250 --> 00:20:53.828
That's just like the bookie
standing by.

00:20:53.828 --> 00:20:59.484
You now are going to take
advantage of the fact that you

00:20:59.484 --> 00:21:05.553
can anticipate that the market
will stand there ready to bet

00:21:05.553 --> 00:21:06.890
with you.
 

00:21:06.890 --> 00:21:09.843
Now, if the whole market
freezes or something you can be

00:21:09.843 --> 00:21:10.808
totally screwed.
 

00:21:10.808 --> 00:21:15.769
You're doing your complicated
dynamic betting with the market,

00:21:15.769 --> 00:21:18.182
one day you wake up and you
can't bet anymore because

00:21:18.182 --> 00:21:20.500
nobody's willing to trade,
something horrible has

00:21:20.500 --> 00:21:22.618
happened, 9/11 happened or
something like that.

00:21:22.618 --> 00:21:25.906
You can be caught in a really
bad situation and end up running

00:21:25.906 --> 00:21:26.769
a lot of risk.
 

00:21:26.769 --> 00:21:31.340
So you're relying on the
market, so it's not surprising

00:21:31.340 --> 00:21:36.250
that when the market freezes up
lots of people suddenly are

00:21:36.250 --> 00:21:40.230
exposed to more risk than they
were before.

00:21:40.230 --> 00:21:43.086
So now in the market you're not
going to be able to find these

00:21:43.086 --> 00:21:43.930
pure arbitrages.
 

00:21:43.930 --> 00:21:46.828
In the sports example it was a
pure arbitrage.

00:21:46.828 --> 00:21:50.315
There was a Philly fan who is
betting at even odds and a

00:21:50.315 --> 00:21:52.848
bookie who was betting at 3 to 2
odds.

00:21:52.848 --> 00:21:55.230
Now, you shouldn't expect that
to happen.

00:21:55.230 --> 00:21:59.165
I mean, by what miracle did
this fan come to you instead of

00:21:59.165 --> 00:22:00.660
to the other bookie?
 

00:22:00.660 --> 00:22:04.618
Why do you deserve to meet this
fan and take advantage of him?

00:22:04.618 --> 00:22:07.240
What have you got that no other
bookie has?

00:22:07.240 --> 00:22:09.601
It's a miracle he came to you
and not to one of the other

00:22:09.601 --> 00:22:10.358
hundred bookies.
 

00:22:10.358 --> 00:22:13.835
Well, it's probably because you
actually know something that the

00:22:13.835 --> 00:22:16.759
other bookies don't that you can
take advantage of.

00:22:16.759 --> 00:22:21.433
So in the background here
there's another thing that you

00:22:21.433 --> 00:22:22.028
knew.
 

00:22:22.028 --> 00:22:25.019
You knew the fan was going to
pay off if he lost.

00:22:25.019 --> 00:22:28.087
Maybe the other bookies weren't
willing to bet with him because

00:22:28.087 --> 00:22:30.808
they didn't think he was going
to pay off if he lost.

00:22:30.808 --> 00:22:33.915
So that's the extra thing that
you knew, you knew that he was

00:22:33.915 --> 00:22:34.900
going to pay off.
 

00:22:34.900 --> 00:22:37.769
Now it makes sense that he came
to you and not to the other

00:22:37.769 --> 00:22:40.838
bookies because you actually
knew something that they don't.

00:22:40.838 --> 00:22:44.759
And so that's how it really
works in the market.

00:22:44.759 --> 00:22:47.765
You're relying on some piece of
information you have that they

00:22:47.765 --> 00:22:48.160
don't.
 

00:22:48.160 --> 00:22:50.163
Of course you could be wrong
about that information and then

00:22:50.163 --> 00:22:51.250
you get into a lot of trouble.
 

00:22:51.250 --> 00:22:53.944
So here in this mortgage what's
the thing that you're relying

00:22:53.944 --> 00:22:54.170
on?
 

00:22:54.170 --> 00:22:59.500
I'm assuming that the rest of
the market is standing by ready,

00:22:59.500 --> 00:23:03.412
as I said, to trade,
to make interest rate bets with

00:23:03.412 --> 00:23:05.114
you,
with everybody,

00:23:05.114 --> 00:23:09.306
at even odds whether the
interest rate's going to go up

00:23:09.306 --> 00:23:10.160
or down.
 

00:23:10.160 --> 00:23:12.682
So no matter where you find
yourself in the future,

00:23:12.682 --> 00:23:15.558
like here, someone is willing
to bet at 50/50 odds that it

00:23:15.558 --> 00:23:16.720
will go up or down.
 

00:23:16.720 --> 00:23:18.982
Now, this is a year-long bet so
you're going to have to take

00:23:18.982 --> 00:23:20.250
into account the interest rate.
 

00:23:20.250 --> 00:23:22.680
It's not just going to be 50/50.
 

00:23:22.680 --> 00:23:25.866
You have to discount all the
cash flows by the interest rate,

00:23:25.866 --> 00:23:29.319
but it's basically a 50/50 bet
discounted by the interest rate.

00:23:29.319 --> 00:23:33.640
So now what's new here?
 

00:23:33.640 --> 00:23:36.038
Well, you don't know what the
cash flows are.

00:23:36.038 --> 00:23:39.308
So here's the extra piece of
information you're adding.

00:23:39.308 --> 00:23:43.968
You know that the mortgage
homeowner is rational and is

00:23:43.968 --> 00:23:46.470
going to prepay rationally.
 

00:23:46.470 --> 00:23:48.548
So you know what these cash
flows are.

00:23:48.548 --> 00:23:51.132
Some of the time the mortgage
homeowner is going to pay the 8

00:23:51.132 --> 00:23:53.112
dollars he owes,
some of the time he's just

00:23:53.112 --> 00:23:55.832
going to pay 8 dollars,
in fact, here is what you know

00:23:55.832 --> 00:23:56.900
is going to happen.
 

00:23:56.900 --> 00:24:00.298
Down here where the 1s are he's
going to pay his coupon of 8,

00:24:00.298 --> 00:24:03.640
pay off the remaining principal
and that's the end of it.

00:24:03.640 --> 00:24:07.423
So in fact the very first day
if interest rates went down the

00:24:07.423 --> 00:24:11.019
rational thing to do is to pay
off the entire mortgage.

00:24:11.019 --> 00:24:13.038
So you know that's going to
happen.

00:24:13.038 --> 00:24:15.509
Now, that's the extra
information you have.

00:24:15.509 --> 00:24:18.038
You know what the cash flows
are.

00:24:18.038 --> 00:24:21.505
If other people knew those cash
flows they would figure out the

00:24:21.505 --> 00:24:23.069
price of the mortgage too.
 

00:24:23.069 --> 00:24:24.298
It's just they don't know those.
 

00:24:24.298 --> 00:24:29.101
You know the cash flows and you
can now figure out that the

00:24:29.101 --> 00:24:30.838
price better be 98.
 

00:24:30.838 --> 00:24:35.048
Why--if there's someone else
willing to trade with you to buy

00:24:35.048 --> 00:24:39.328
that mortgage for more than 98,
like why might that happen?

00:24:39.328 --> 00:24:42.759
Because someone else might have
the erroneous opinion that the

00:24:42.759 --> 00:24:45.118
homeowner will never call the
mortgage,

00:24:45.118 --> 00:24:47.810
will never prepay because he's
just going to be asleep all the

00:24:47.810 --> 00:24:48.118
time.
 

00:24:48.118 --> 00:24:52.298
So let's say the homeowner's a
she.

00:24:52.298 --> 00:24:54.680
Let's say the homeowners are
all shes.

00:24:54.680 --> 00:24:58.078
This other trader thinks
they're all asleep and will

00:24:58.078 --> 00:24:59.078
never prepay.
 

00:24:59.078 --> 00:25:02.671
You know that these homeowners
are all incredibly alert and on

00:25:02.671 --> 00:25:05.320
top of things,
and so they're going to prepay,

00:25:05.320 --> 00:25:06.970
and the value's only 98.
 

00:25:06.970 --> 00:25:10.836
So because of that extra
information you know the actual

00:25:10.836 --> 00:25:11.750
cash flows.
 

00:25:11.750 --> 00:25:13.240
Sorry, we're here.
 

00:25:13.240 --> 00:25:14.420
You know the cash flows.
 

00:25:14.420 --> 00:25:18.390
You know how to value the bond,
and you know it's worth 98.

00:25:18.390 --> 00:25:22.011
So, and let's say the other
guy's willing to pay you 120 for

00:25:22.011 --> 00:25:22.319
it.
 

00:25:22.319 --> 00:25:23.920
So you can sell it short.
 

00:25:23.920 --> 00:25:27.538
You can sell it to the guy
short for 120.

00:25:27.538 --> 00:25:30.578
That means you owe whatever
cash flows the mortgage pays,

00:25:30.578 --> 00:25:33.240
