01:00:31.420 --> 01:00:32.590
So it's paying 9 plus that.
 

01:00:32.590 --> 01:00:35.440
So it's 130 and here it's 168.
 

01:00:35.440 --> 01:00:37.289
The gap is still 38.
 

01:00:37.289 --> 01:00:43.780
So I want 1 sixth of 130.
 

01:00:43.780 --> 01:00:52.360
So 1 sixth of 130 costs--it's
still the same number.

01:00:52.360 --> 01:00:53.469
It's 22.
 

01:00:53.469 --> 01:00:56.018
I did bad arithmetic to begin
with so it's still 22.

01:00:56.018 --> 01:00:59.927
No, sorry, it's 1 sixth of this
thing which is 140,

01:00:59.927 --> 01:01:01.489
so it's 23, right.
 

01:01:01.489 --> 01:01:01.980
Sorry.
 

01:01:01.980 --> 01:01:02.539
That didn't change.
 

01:01:02.539 --> 01:01:07.050
So the payment here is 130 and
the payment here is 168.

01:01:07.050 --> 01:01:12.012
So 1 sixth of 130,
that's the up payment,

01:01:12.012 --> 01:01:15.610
and this is 1 sixth of 168.
 

01:01:15.610 --> 01:01:21.088
Now, I want that plus whatever
the 1 year Treasury gives me to

01:01:21.088 --> 01:01:24.949
equal 100.6 up here and 107.11
down here.

01:01:24.949 --> 01:01:27.706
That way I would have
replicated things and hedged

01:01:27.706 --> 01:01:29.170
myself perfectly,
right?

01:01:29.170 --> 01:01:31.639
But I don't have to figure out
what that 1 year Treasury is.

01:01:31.639 --> 01:01:32.739
I think it's obvious.
 

01:01:32.739 --> 01:01:38.010
All I have to do is say
subtract 23 from 98.8,

01:01:38.010 --> 01:01:42.050
so I just have to buy 75.8
dollars worth of the 1 year

01:01:42.050 --> 01:01:46.320
Treasury and that'll give me
