01:02:20.880 --> 01:02:23.349
which is it's 50 percent likely
discounted,

01:02:23.349 --> 01:02:27.195
multiplying by its payoff 130,
plus 1 half discounted

01:02:27.195 --> 01:02:29.710
multiplied by the payoff of 168.
 

01:02:29.710 --> 01:02:32.550
This is 168 because it's a 9
percent bond.

01:02:32.550 --> 01:02:37.268
So it's 1 sixth times 1
sixth--so if I get a sixth of

01:02:37.268 --> 01:02:42.440
the bond it'll cost me 140.43
divided by 6 which is 23.

01:02:42.440 --> 01:02:45.849
So what about the 1 year
Treasury?

01:02:45.849 --> 01:02:49.882
That's going to give me some
payment, an additional payment

01:02:49.882 --> 01:02:52.804
here and here,
namely 1.06 times whatever I

01:02:52.804 --> 01:02:53.570
put in.
 

01:02:53.570 --> 01:02:59.626
So you notice that the gap
between here and here since I've

01:02:59.626 --> 01:03:06.309
multiplied by 1 sixth is exactly
this 6 and 1 half dollar gap.

01:03:06.309 --> 01:03:14.139
So the total I have to spend is
98.8 over here,

01:03:14.139 --> 01:03:17.525
so if I spend 23 dollars on the
Treasury and the remaining

01:03:17.525 --> 01:03:20.177
amount--
23 dollars on the 30 year 9

01:03:20.177 --> 01:03:23.268
percent bond,
the remaining amount of money

01:03:23.268 --> 01:03:27.032
which is 75.8 on the Treasury I
will have spent this 98.8

01:03:27.032 --> 01:03:29.606
dollars,
but then I have to get the same

01:03:29.606 --> 01:03:30.119
payoffs.
 

01:03:30.119 --> 01:03:30.949
Why is that?
 

01:03:30.949 --> 01:03:33.382
Because they're all being
priced at the same prices,

01:03:33.382 --> 01:03:35.768
so it's just the distributive
law of arithmetic.

01:03:35.768 --> 01:03:40.849
If these payoffs times 1 sixth
plus the Treasury payoffs equal

01:03:40.849 --> 01:03:45.764
100.6 and 107.11 then it must be
that the sum of the money I

01:03:45.764 --> 01:03:49.179
spent on the 30 year 9 percent
bond,

01:03:49.179 --> 01:03:52.632
plus the sum of the money I
spent on the Treasury has to

01:03:52.632 --> 01:03:53.449
equal 98.8.
 

01:03:53.449 --> 01:03:59.637
Therefore, I know that the
amount of money of the 98.8 I

01:03:59.637 --> 01:04:06.836
spent on the 1 year Treasury was
98.8 minus the 23 I spent on the

01:04:06.836 --> 01:04:08.750
30-year bond.
 

01:04:08.750 --> 01:04:13.202
So that's how you can--so to
say it again just in a big

01:04:13.202 --> 01:04:14.440
picture look.
 

01:04:14.440 --> 01:04:16.119
There are two things that can
happen.

01:04:16.119 --> 01:04:19.052
If you hold two bonds,
a 1-year Treasury and a 30-year

01:04:19.052 --> 01:04:21.007
thing,
you're obviously going to be

01:04:21.007 --> 01:04:24.186
able to match these two things
by holding the right proportion

01:04:24.186 --> 01:04:24.760
of them.
 

01:04:24.760 --> 01:04:26.750
That is just obvious.
 

01:04:26.750 --> 01:04:30.246
And then less obvious is how
quickly I'm figuring out how

01:04:30.246 --> 01:04:32.369
much of those two bonds to hold.
 

01:04:32.369 --> 01:04:35.632
And the way I'm figuring it out
so quickly is because the 1-year

01:04:35.632 --> 01:04:38.170
Treasury is paying the same
thing up and down,

01:04:38.170 --> 01:04:40.682
so I have to get all the
variation out of the 30-year

01:04:40.682 --> 01:04:43.166
bond,
so I have to hold the right

01:04:43.166 --> 01:04:47.670
proportion of the 30-year bond
to get the same variation.

01:04:47.670 --> 01:04:51.938
So in the very big picture if
you're trying to hedge some

01:04:51.938 --> 01:04:55.900
instrument with another
instrument and a portfolio of

01:04:55.900 --> 01:04:58.429
stuff,
much of which is certain,

01:04:58.429 --> 01:05:00.730
and only one thing that's
risky,

01:05:00.730 --> 01:05:03.657
the amount of the risky thing
you have to hold has to produce

01:05:03.657 --> 01:05:06.389
as much variation as the thing
you're trying to hedge.

01:05:06.389 --> 01:05:09.643
So the key is being able to
tell at a glance how much

01:05:09.643 --> 01:05:13.396
variation each thing has then
you can tell in what proportion

01:05:13.396 --> 01:05:14.460
to hold them.
 

01:05:14.460 --> 01:05:18.039
And so the very last thing I
want to tell you today,

01:05:18.039 --> 01:05:20.070
which is unfortunately going to
take me a few minutes,

01:05:20.070 --> 01:05:24.543
is how traders look at
variation and can guess it

01:05:24.543 --> 01:05:26.500
incredibly quickly.
 

01:05:26.500 --> 01:05:29.784
So a trader could look at this
and guess without doing almost

01:05:29.784 --> 01:05:32.139
any calculations what the right
hedge is.

01:05:32.139 --> 01:05:40.766
So just like we did the
doubling rule I want to do the

01:05:40.766 --> 01:05:45.000
variation rule of thumb.
 

01:05:45.000 --> 01:05:54.059
And this is called duration and
convexity, or average life.

01:05:54.059 --> 01:05:58.684
So I asked myself,
suppose I have this 30-year

01:05:58.684 --> 01:06:03.617
bond, 30-year non-callable bond,
that's this one,

01:06:03.617 --> 01:06:05.570
9 percent bond.
 

01:06:05.570 --> 01:06:08.648
How could I guess,
kind of, what the variation in

01:06:08.648 --> 01:06:11.150
price would be without having to
do,

01:06:11.150 --> 01:06:14.271
you know, I've had to do this
very complicated backward

01:06:14.271 --> 01:06:15.659
induction calculation.
 

01:06:15.659 --> 01:06:19.644
Now, remember once the interest
rates go up here it's a random

01:06:19.644 --> 01:06:22.389
walk so on average they're
pretty much,

01:06:22.389 --> 01:06:24.985
not pretty much,
they're exactly what they were

01:06:24.985 --> 01:06:25.380
here.
 

01:06:25.380 --> 01:06:26.480
They start here.
 

01:06:26.480 --> 01:06:28.940
They go up and down,
but on average they're still

01:06:28.940 --> 01:06:29.300
here.
 

01:06:29.300 --> 01:06:32.385
And over here they've gone down
so the average is lower going

01:06:32.385 --> 01:06:32.900
forward.
 

01:06:32.900 --> 01:06:35.268
In fact, it's exactly equal to
that.

01:06:35.268 --> 01:06:39.672
So if you're a trader and there
was no uncertainty you would

01:06:39.672 --> 01:06:44.224
know that the present value with
no uncertainty is going to be

01:06:44.224 --> 01:06:48.550
the coupon divided by (1 the
interest rate) the coupon over

01:06:48.550 --> 01:06:52.878
(1 the interest rate) squared
(in the last year) the coupon

01:06:52.878 --> 01:06:57.132
over (1 the interest rate) to
the T 100 times [correction:

01:06:57.132 --> 01:07:00.639
over]
(1 the interest rate) to the T.

01:07:00.639 --> 01:07:02.829
That's the value of the bond.
 

01:07:02.829 --> 01:07:07.210
Now, you sort of want to know
how much is that price going to

01:07:07.210 --> 01:07:10.130
change when the interest rate
changes.

01:07:10.130 --> 01:07:13.438
Well, at a glance,
I mean, you just take the

01:07:13.438 --> 01:07:14.440
derivative.
 

01:07:14.440 --> 01:07:19.559
What is dPV/dr?
 

01:07:19.559 --> 01:07:30.110
It's going to be minus C over
(1 r) squared - 2 C over (1 r)

01:07:30.110 --> 01:07:41.199
cubed - T times C over (1 r) to
the (T 1) - T times 100 divided

01:07:41.199 --> 01:07:45.849
by (1 r) to the (T 1).
 

01:07:45.849 --> 01:07:48.489
That's the derivative.
 

01:07:48.489 --> 01:07:51.230
It looks like I'm making things
even more complicated,

01:07:51.230 --> 01:07:57.755
you would think,
but this turns out to be not so

01:07:57.755 --> 01:08:02.027
complicated,
because this is a number--so

01:08:02.027 --> 01:08:04.920
let's put the minus on the
outside,

01:08:04.920 --> 01:08:10.039
so I'll get rid of this.
 

01:08:10.039 --> 01:08:13.630
This is a number which you can
sort of get in your head,

01:08:13.630 --> 01:08:15.329
so let's try writing it.
 

01:08:15.329 --> 01:08:17.738
Let's pull out one of the (1
r)s.

01:08:17.738 --> 01:08:27.546
So it's minus 1 over (1 r)
times (C over (1 r) 2 C over (1

01:08:27.546 --> 01:08:30.300
r) squared ...
 

01:08:30.300 --> 01:08:38.529
T times (C 100) (that's the
last payment) over (1 r) to the

01:08:38.529 --> 01:08:39.239
T).
 

01:08:39.239 --> 01:08:42.670
Now, what is that?
 

01:08:42.670 --> 01:08:44.300
Can you interpret that?
 

01:08:44.300 --> 01:08:47.454
And the answer is yes you can
interpret that because what is

01:08:47.454 --> 01:08:47.828
that?
 

01:08:47.828 --> 01:08:51.586
That's saying these are all the
payments you're getting over the

01:08:51.586 --> 01:08:52.720
life of the bond.
 

01:08:52.720 --> 01:08:55.229
It's C, C and the last one's C
100.

01:08:55.229 --> 01:08:57.829
This number that keeps coming
in front of them,

01:08:57.829 --> 01:09:01.109
though, is the year in which
you're getting the payment.

01:09:01.109 --> 01:09:02.319
This is in the first year.
 

01:09:02.319 --> 01:09:03.250
I could put a 1 there.
 

01:09:03.250 --> 01:09:04.840
This is the payment in the
second year.

01:09:04.840 --> 01:09:05.729
There's a 2 here.
 

01:09:05.729 --> 01:09:07.520
This is the payment in the Tth
year.

01:09:07.520 --> 01:09:09.029
There's a T here.
 

01:09:09.029 --> 01:09:12.479
You got that T from taking the
derivative of the denominator

01:09:12.479 --> 01:09:12.890
here.
 

01:09:12.890 --> 01:09:19.283
So it's like weighting the year
in which the payments come by

01:09:19.283 --> 01:09:22.479
the value of those payments.
 

01:09:22.479 --> 01:09:24.368
So in the first year the value
is C.

01:09:24.368 --> 01:09:26.198
The present value is C over (1
r).

01:09:26.198 --> 01:09:28.640
In the second year the payment
is C,

01:09:28.640 --> 01:09:31.658
but discounted,
C over (1 r) squared,

01:09:31.658 --> 01:09:34.750
and the last year the total
payment is C 100,

01:09:34.750 --> 01:09:37.279
but you had to discount it by
(1 r) to the Tth.

01:09:37.279 --> 01:09:42.020
So this is just like taking the
average year in which the

01:09:42.020 --> 01:09:45.069
present value flows actually
come.

01:09:45.069 --> 01:09:50.340
If I divided this now by the
present value of--

01:09:50.340 --> 01:09:55.270
the present value,
these numbers down here,

01:09:55.270 --> 01:09:59.970
C over this C over this squared
C 100 over this to the Tth,

01:09:59.970 --> 01:10:02.640
those are all weights
multiplying the year in which

01:10:02.640 --> 01:10:03.710
the payments come.
 

01:10:03.710 --> 01:10:05.340
They add up to the present
value.

01:10:05.340 --> 01:10:09.122
So basically I've just got a
weighted average of what year

01:10:09.122 --> 01:10:10.649
the payments come in.
 

01:10:10.649 --> 01:10:18.680
This is called the average life.
 

01:10:18.680 --> 01:10:21.730
This thing in here is the
average life because I've

01:10:21.730 --> 01:10:25.391
multiplied the year in which the
payments come by the present

01:10:25.391 --> 01:10:28.626
value of the cash flows there
and then I've made those

01:10:28.626 --> 01:10:31.800
multipliers add up to 1 by
dividing by the PV.

01:10:31.800 --> 01:10:36.189
See, this in parenthesis,
all these terms are the things

01:10:36.189 --> 01:10:39.939
multiplying the year in which
the thing came.

01:10:39.939 --> 01:10:42.708
So if I add up all these
coefficients here I'm just

01:10:42.708 --> 01:10:44.260
getting the present value.
 

01:10:44.260 --> 01:10:45.828
So now the coefficients add up
to 1.

01:10:45.828 --> 01:10:48.774
So I'm just taking an average
of the year in which the thing

01:10:48.774 --> 01:10:50.970
came and that's what the average
life is,

01:10:50.970 --> 01:10:55.563
but that's equal to the
derivative of the present value

01:10:55.563 --> 01:10:58.198
divided by the present value.
 

01:10:58.198 --> 01:11:00.756
So it's--the percentage change
in the present value is the

01:11:00.756 --> 01:11:02.640
average year in which the
payments come.

01:11:02.640 --> 01:11:03.970
So let's just think about it.
 

01:11:03.970 --> 01:11:05.908
Suppose you have a 10-year bond?
 

01:11:05.908 --> 01:11:09.158
It pays C, C,
C, C, C, and then 100 at the

01:11:09.158 --> 01:11:10.029
very end.
 

01:11:10.029 --> 01:11:12.479
What do you think the average
life is?

01:11:12.479 --> 01:11:15.186
Well, if there were no
discounting the average life

01:11:15.186 --> 01:11:18.600
wouldn't be 5 because there's
such a huge payment in the end.

01:11:18.600 --> 01:11:23.168
The average life would be 8 or
9, but there is discounting so

01:11:23.168 --> 01:11:26.520
this thing at the end won't
count as much.

01:11:26.520 --> 01:11:28.408
So the average life is probably
7.

01:11:28.408 --> 01:11:30.773
If it's a 30 year bond,
the average life,

01:11:30.773 --> 01:11:33.787
you're going to get C,
C, C, C, and then all the way

01:11:33.787 --> 01:11:36.210
at the end you're going to get C
100.

01:11:36.210 --> 01:11:39.345
Well, if the payments were all
equal and no discounting it

01:11:39.345 --> 01:11:41.744
would be 15,
but there's a huge amount of

01:11:41.744 --> 01:11:45.288
discounting so that last payment
is really pretty irrelevant,

01:11:45.288 --> 01:11:47.840
so probably--so it's not clear
which way it goes,

01:11:47.840 --> 01:11:52.270
probably the average life will
be less than 15.

01:11:52.270 --> 01:11:56.550
So you can see just by looking
at the bond,

01:11:56.550 --> 01:12:00.266
and I'm ending with this
thought, by looking at the bond

01:12:00.266 --> 01:12:03.850
itself you can figure out what
the average life is.

01:12:03.850 --> 01:12:06.028
So a trader,
just by a little experience and

01:12:06.028 --> 01:12:08.003
common sense,
can figure out the average

01:12:08.003 --> 01:12:08.460
life.
 

01:12:08.460 --> 01:12:10.710
I mean, here are all the
payments the way they're coming.

01:12:10.710 --> 01:12:13.546
They're coming evenly across
the whole history of the bond

01:12:13.546 --> 01:12:16.356
with something at the end,
so the average life is probably

01:12:16.356 --> 01:12:19.015
a little bit over the average,
but if you go way off,

01:12:19.015 --> 01:12:22.070
you push the final payment too
far to the end then it's

01:12:22.070 --> 01:12:24.519
becoming negligible,
it's almost irrelevant,

01:12:24.519 --> 01:12:27.077
and so the average life by
discounting will probably be

01:12:27.077 --> 01:12:28.118
before the average.
 

01:12:28.118 --> 01:12:31.228
So a 10-year bond probably has
an average life of 7,

01:12:31.228 --> 01:12:34.578
a 30-year bond maybe has an
average life of 12 or 13.

01:12:34.578 --> 01:12:38.641
Once you know the average life,
you just have to hold bonds in

01:12:38.641 --> 01:12:41.038
proportion to their average
lives.

01:12:41.038 --> 01:12:44.217
The dollar amount you put in
each bond to hedge it is just

01:12:44.217 --> 01:12:46.170
proportional to its average
life.

01:12:46.170 --> 01:12:48.765
So that's how a trader,
without having to do any

01:12:48.765 --> 01:12:51.505
arithmetic,
can kind of guess how much of

01:12:51.505 --> 01:12:55.300
the 30 year bond will it take to
hedge a 10 year bond,

01:12:55.300 --> 01:12:59.939
and how much of a--so which has
a higher average life?

01:12:59.939 --> 01:13:02.738
The longer the bond the higher
the average life,

01:13:02.738 --> 01:13:06.556
the more sensitive it is to
interest rate changes so the

01:13:06.556 --> 01:13:09.750
less of it you need to hedge
your position,

01:13:09.750 --> 01:13:12.391
so if you hold the 30 year bond
you don't have to hold that much

01:13:12.391 --> 01:13:13.471
of it,
1 sixth of it,

01:13:13.471 --> 01:13:15.130
in order to hedge this
mortgage.

01:13:15.130 --> 01:13:17.942
The mortgage has a very short
average life because it's

01:13:17.942 --> 01:13:19.140
prepaying so quickly.
 

01:13:19.140 --> 01:13:20.770
So it's not going to last very
long.

01:13:20.770 --> 01:13:23.667
So this is an amazing
connection between average life

01:13:23.667 --> 01:13:25.618
and sensitivity to interest
rate.

01:13:25.618 --> 01:13:27.550
And average life is something
you can guess.

01:13:27.550 --> 01:13:30.212
Sensitivity to interest rate is
something you have to do huge

01:13:30.212 --> 01:13:32.119
calculations for,
but the two are almost the

01:13:32.119 --> 01:13:32.520
same.
 

